Introducing Ken Swift, the epitome of breaking culture! We had the honor of capturing his movements during a motion capture session at Purdue University in January 2022, using an innovative approach to preserve the legacy of his iconic style. With this data, we can better understand the fundamental techniques and styles of breaking, as well as archive them.

So blessed to be here in the world to experience 50 Years of, what would be now known as Hip Hop Culture. Peace to the elders, architects 1st and  foremost, …. and then, after,  the generations of this culture from the late 1970’s and 1980’s in the Bronx and other boroughs as it progressed in NYC and then around the world. 

This article came out yesterday in The NY Times Magazine, which is always inside the full NY Times Newspaper. There is so much to read and reminisce on all these 50 years of Hip Hop most of all with “Rap culture”  which is great. With this article , alongside that, I am happy that they put this picture up of Breaking, a true element of this culture - and, I which I would say is the first true dance of Hip Hop. This pic is from the first tour of Hip Hop - The New York City Rap Tour” NYC to Europe 1982. - this is everything to me to be with “Frosty Freeze”  and “Take 1” in this same pic, Frosty to me was the best bboy in my area -yes, there were nasty bboys uptown no question but he had something different.  We are talking about Uptown West Side NYC - 82nd street to 105th street - Amsterdam / Columbus Avenues, jus like that. I speak about many others because my word is bond. - yes loving this pic - and, my brother Take 1 - the writer/bboy who is our brother who connected us to Henry and - just sayin - it was Take 1 who would connect us young bboys/writers with the exhibitions with Henry for the Village Voice magazine exposure -  Take 1 and Frosty are true family bothers - and I just want to take this moment to give them their love and respect as they rest in Peace. For this to be released on my birthday in The NY Times on my birthday Sunday August 13, is just crazy.  And I’m happy,…. My mom too. 🙂. The best thing about this picture is Take  1 and Frosty Freeze.

- just an incredible moment to be able to say hello and say Thank you and shake the hand of a legendary music influence - American jazz keyboardist, arranger and record producer Bob James after his concert with both amazing Michael Palazzolo and James Adkins at The Catalina Jazz Club in LA.  In the late 1970’s I first heard his music on Bronx jam cassette tapes, then, through my boy Doze as we started DJing, who shuffled through his stepdads record collection without knowing but finding a few of his albums in our search for Breaks.  From that point Jazz music was really interesting so to find breaks we would look through any jazz artists albums if we could, it opened my mind up to the complete diverse genre of what is “Hip Hop” music.  #bobjames #catalinajazzclubla #breaklifenyc @bobjamesmusic  @michaelpalazzolobass @jamesalexadkins @dozegreen

Had a really cool opportunity to be a part of a screening and panel on behalf of the 40th Anniversary of the documentary film “Style Wars”, screened at The Museum Of the City of New York. Moderated by my friend Jessica Green. I was a shy young kid coming up in the 1980’s, I wasn’t in the film Style Wars much at all but I will never forget the moments we all had. Thank you Henry, Rest in Peace Tony Silver, Take 1, King Kase 2,  Kippy Dee, Frosty Freeze, and so many more that have passed on. To just chill with, and see Riff 170, TKid, Lady Pink, Skeme and so many more was just really cool. It was a sold out event – and I had such a cool time. Oh, and gotta give my boy “Kid Freeze Dynamic Rockers” his props, he came through on the strength and also among many Shauna, Ono, Totem TC5.  Yup.
